and give
some credit to the Afghans as
well that they

28:40.953 --> 28:45.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are very much shouldering the
burden of fighting
and in many cases dying for
their country.

28:45.724 --> 28:52.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it is a very challenged,
troubled, difficult
country, and has been throughout
its history.

28:52.164 --> 28:53.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ambassador
Edelman, Afghanistan?

28:53.966 --> 28:58.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC EDELMAN: I largely agree
with what both
Philip and General Petraeus have
said.

28:58.503 --> 29:05.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would say that I think the
president's decision
to set a timeline at the outset
of the surge

29:05.177 --> 29:06.078 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Afghanistan...

29:06.178 --> 29:07.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Publicly.

29:08.080 --> 29:10.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ERIC EDELMAN: Publicly --
created difficulties
that made it, I think, a harder
row to hoe

29:11.049 --> 29:16.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for General Petraeus and General
Allen and
others who succeeded them.

29:16.188 --> 29:20.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I -- like General Petraeus, I
give the president
enormous credit for reversing
himself and

29:20.559 --> 29:24.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not insisting on a complete
withdrawal during
his time in office.

29:24.596 --> 29:30.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I do think the new
administration is going
to be facing a very tough
situation.

29:30.302 --> 29:32.037 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I agree with General
Petraeus.

29:32.137 --> 29:36.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to keep in mind that the
reason we
went there to begin with is not
to allow it

29:36.241 --> 29:43.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be a kind of petri dish for
Islamic extremism
that seeks to attack the United
States.

29:43.749 --> 29:45.484 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

29:45.584 --> 29:47.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID PETRAEUS: And my hope
would be that
there could be a sustained
commitment at,

29:47.486 --> 29:53.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
again, a modest level that is a
sustainable
strategy in terms of...

29:53.325 --> 29:54.393 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

29:54.493 --> 29:55.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You mean in the
next administration?

29:55.327 --> 29:56.228 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

29:56.328 --> 29:57.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID PETRAEUS: Yes.

29:57.329 --> 29:58.230 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

29:58.330 --> 30:00.032 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

30:00.132 --> 30:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: General Petraeus,
you told
us that Syria, the last place I
want to ask

30:02.000 --> 30:04.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you all about, is a place in
which history
is going to judge this
administration most

30:04.536 --> 30:05.437 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
harshly.

30:05.537 --> 30:06.438 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Why?

30:06.538 --> 30:08.373 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

30:08.473 --> 30:11.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID PETRAEUS: Well, I think
what's happened
in Syria is that we have had
rhetoric that

30:11.209 --> 30:22.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has not, in the end, been backed
up by resources
and commitment, Bashar must go,
a red line

30:22.721 --> 30:25.490 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
discussion of what a
humanitarian catastrophe
it was.

30:25.590 --> 30:31.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, at the end of the day, we
haven't made
the very, very difficult -- and,
again, there

30:31.363 --> 30:33.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are no easy choices about Syria.

30:33.398 --> 30:34.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was at the table.

30:34.433 --> 30:36.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There were never guarantees.

30:36.501 --> 30:41.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we didn't take the very
tough decisions
that could have given us a
chance in some

30:41.740 --> 30:48.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of these cases, and where you're
pretty certain
that if there wasn't a decision
or not sufficient

30:48.580 --> 30:53.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resources, that it wasn't going
to succeed,
in the way that we defined
success at the

30:54.086 --> 30:55.854 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
time.

30:55.954 --> 30:59.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Phil Gordon, why
was President
Obama right not to retaliate, do
something

30:59.758 --> 31:04.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a military nature after
President Assad
crossed that red line?

31:04.329 --> 31:07.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHILIP GORDON: Well, I actually
think he should
have done something of a
military nature after

31:07.799 --> 31:09.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he crossed that red line.

31:09.334 --> 31:10.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That was about chemical weapons.

31:10.669 --> 31:13.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And he said, if they used
chemical weapons,
he would respond.

31:13.472 --> 31:17.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I don't think we should
confuse that with
the broader question of using
military force

31:17.776 --> 31:21.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to achieve our broader goals in
Syria, like
getting rid of the Assad regime.

31:21.980 --> 31:26.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there, if your question is
why was he
right, I think people should be
very careful

31:26.818 --> 31:32.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not to assume there was some
modest use of
military force that would have
achieved the

31:32.424 --> 31:37.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
objective of getting rid of the
regime and
putting moderates in charge of a
stable Syria.

31:37.295 --> 31:41.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In that sense, I think General
Petraeus is
right that there was a gap
between the rhetoric,

31:41.733 --> 31:43.602 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the ends and the means.

31:43.702 --> 31:49.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the critique that somehow,
if only the
president had given more arms to
the opposition

31:49.207 --> 31:54.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or set up a no-fly zone, that
gap would have
been closed, I disagree with.

31:54.179 --> 31:56.014 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ambassador
Edelman?

31:56.114 --> 32:00.018 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ERIC EDELMAN: Well, the
administration's argument
for inaction in Syria was that
doing some

32:00.118 --> 32:04.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the things that Philip just
suggested would
lead to greater violence,
greater extremism,

32:04.823 --> 32:10.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more radicalization, and in
general a worse
humanitarian situation in Syria.

32:10.862 --> 32:14.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
However, there are consequences
to inaction
as well.

32:14.132 --> 32:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the inaction that we saw, I
think, has
led to a catastrophic situation,
half-a-million

32:20.005 --> 32:26.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people killed, 11 million people
displaced,
a migration crisis that is
overwhelming the

32:26.278 --> 32:29.314 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
institutions of Europe, our
closest allies.

32:29.414 --> 32:31.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I do think -- I agree with
General Petraeus.

32:31.249 --> 32:34.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, in retrospect, when
people judge
this administration
historically, it will

32:34.619 --> 32:36.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be seen as the biggest stain on
this administration's
record.

32:36.955 --> 32:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHILIP GORDON: I think that
summary of the
consequences of inaction is fair
and accurate.

32:41.593 --> 32:46.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No one who was involved with
this policy would
disagree that the consequences
of the road

32:47.065 --> 32:48.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
traveled were poor.

32:49.034 --> 32:55.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, again, we have to be
careful not to assume
that the alternative course of
action, using

32:55.941 --> 33:01.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
military force, for example,
would have had
led to a better set of
circumstances.

33:01.513 --> 33:02.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It would be different
circumstances.

33:02.581 --> 33:04.382 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

33:04.482 --> 33:06.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID PETRAEUS: I do think we
have to be a
little careful not to say that
it was either

33:06.418 --> 33:12.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this or either that, that it was
either all-out
military action to get rid of
Bashar or it

33:12.591 --> 33:14.292 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was nothing.

33:14.392 --> 33:18.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I do think there were
alternatives, as have
been discussed by the
participants.

33:18.396 --> 33:23.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, no guarantee that they
would have succeeded,
but it's hard to imagine the
situation could

33:24.069 --> 33:25.871 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be worse than it is right now.

33:25.971 --> 33:28.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we know
we're going to
be debating all three of these
places we have

33:28.907 --> 33:33.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talked about just now and the
rest of that
part of the world for a long
time to come.

33:33.445 --> 33:35.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For now, we thank all of you for
being here,
General David Petraeus,
Ambassador Eric Edelman,

33:35.247 --> 33:36.147 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Philip Gordon.

33:36.248 --> 33:37.115 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

33:37.215 --> 33:38.116 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID PETRAEUS: Pleasure.

33:38.216 --> 33:40.652 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PHILIP GORDON: Good to be here.

33:40.752 --> 33:51.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

33:51.196 --> 33:53.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now to the analysis of Shields
and Brooks.

33:53.398 --> 33:58.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is syndicated columnist
Mark Shields
and New York Times columnist
David Brooks.

33:58.136 --> 33:59.905 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you both.

34:00.005 --> 34:03.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is so much to talk about,
but let's
start with talking about the
president-elect

34:03.642 --> 34:05.377 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Russia.

34:05.477 --> 34:08.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We had the news today -- on top
of all the
confirmation that the Russians
interfered

34:08.813 --> 34:12.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the U.S. election, today, we
learned -- and
we talked about earlier it on
the show -- David,

34:12.384 --> 34:18.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that General Michael Flynn had
phone conversations
with the Russian ambassador in
December, several

34:18.223 --> 34:20.125 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of them.

34:20.225 --> 34:23.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we're learning that the
Senate Intelligence
Committee is going to expand
what was already

34:23.528 --> 34:29.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
an investigation into the
Russian interference
into in election to look at any
contacts between

34:29.234 --> 34:33.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Trump campaign and the
Russians and the
Clinton campaign, although the
main focus

34:33.805 --> 34:34.873 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is Donald Trump.

34:34.973 --> 34:36.641 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do we make of all this?

34:36.741 --> 34:39.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I was first struck
by David
Ignatius' comment earlier in the
program that

34:39.477 --> 34:43.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they just could be trying to be
destabilize
the United States across the
board.

34:43.548 --> 34:47.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's a -- I hadn't heard
that thought
before and it's a live
possibility.

34:47.886 --> 34:52.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Putin is someone who has been
undermining
the norms of what we consider
the world order

34:52.390 --> 34:55.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
since he got into power and in
increasing
success.

34:55.593 --> 34:58.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's interesting about the
Trump administration
is how bitterly divided they are
in their

34:58.596 --> 35:00.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
attitudes towards Putin.

35:00.865 --> 35:04.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Steve Bannon and General Flynn
have warm feelings.

35:05.070 --> 35:09.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Putin has been -- and with a lot
of the groups,
the conservative groups, the
more extreme

35:09.541 --> 35:13.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
conservative groups that
underlie Trump, he's
a bit of a hero because he
speaks for traditional

35:13.611 --> 35:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
values, he's against the global
institutions.

35:16.881 --> 35:20.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They see him as someone who has
been on the
defensive from an aggressive
E.U., an aggressive

35:20.785 --> 35:21.753 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
NATO.

35:21.853 --> 35:23.822 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there is a lot of sympathy
there, actually.

35:23.922 --> 35:28.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, if you look at the
more establishment
Republicans, they see him as
what I just described,

35:28.226 --> 35:30.028 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
subversive of the world order.

35:30.128 --> 35:34.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so to me the question will
be, will Trump
and Bannon control policy toward
the foreign

35:34.232 --> 35:37.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
policy, or will everyone else
basically?

35:37.469 --> 35:43.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my money is on everyone
else, because
I think Trump's attention span
is super low.

35:43.274 --> 35:46.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I don't think he has the
expertise to actually
run a foreign policy.

35:46.177 --> 35:48.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at the end of the day -- and
I think this
is a major story of the Trump
administration

35:48.980 --> 35:53.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
-- he's going to want the
affirmation of the
establishment, as he always has.

35:54.052 --> 35:57.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reason he had Clintons at
his wedding
because he wants that
affirmation.

35:57.489 --> 36:00.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When he gets the chance to have
it, I think
he will bend gradually in that
direction.

36:00.392 --> 36:02.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How are you
looking at all
this?

36:02.327 --> 36:06.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Donald Trump is to
traditional
values what I am to marathon
running.

36:06.731 --> 36:07.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

36:07.866 --> 36:09.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: It just doesn't --
it doesn't
fit.

36:09.667 --> 36:14.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I have to say, Judy, I am
perplexed, and I
think an increasing number of
Republicans

36:14.739 --> 36:22.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are perplexed and actually
nervous about Donald
Trump and Russia, nervous in the
sense that

36:22.147 --> 36:26.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he is gratuitously giving
Democrats the national
security advantage, that they're
standing

36:26.885 --> 36:28.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
up for the country.

36:28.853 --> 36:34.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have testimony of General
Mattis, the nominee
for secretary of defense,
asserting that the

36:34.826 --> 36:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
objective, the stated objective
and the mission
of Vladimir Putin's Russia is to
destabilize

36:42.100 --> 36:48.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the North Atlantic Alliance, and
he, who believes
in NATO and believes it's been
one of the

36:48.873 --> 36:57.982 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
great alliances in modern
history, that Putin
represents a threat to this,
that Russia today

36:58.083 --> 37:02.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is nothing but a propaganda arm,
that General
Flynn went to celebrate its
anniversary, sitting

37:03.021 --> 37:07.892 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at Putin's table for money, paid
to show up.

37:07.992 --> 37:12.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I mean, these questions,
essentially,
they have just given it to the
Democrats to

37:12.630 --> 37:16.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stand up and say, wait a minute,
where do
you believe in this country,
plus the suspicions,

37:16.768 --> 37:22.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and real, about in fact the
involvement of
Russia in this election.

37:22.674 --> 37:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question, the real moment of
truth is
going to arrive very shortly, a
couple of

37:26.911 --> 37:31.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
weeks, when sanctions arrive on
Donald Trump's
-- President Donald Trump's desk
passed by

37:31.616 --> 37:33.551 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a Republican Congress.

37:33.651 --> 37:36.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is he going to oppose those
sanctions?

37:36.187 --> 37:37.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's he going to do?

37:37.722 --> 37:43.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just think it's inexplicable
and irrational,
his policy on Russia.

37:44.095 --> 37:45.864 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I would say it's a
theory.

37:45.964 --> 37:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has got a theory of it, which
is the theory
of UKIP in the United Kingdom,
the theory

37:51.269 --> 37:57.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Le Pen in France, which is
that the global
establishment has basically
failed people,

37:57.108 --> 38:01.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that, all around the world
-- it's a little
like Marxism in reverse --
global movement

38:01.312 --> 38:04.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is arising that's against these
institutions
which have failed people.

38:04.883 --> 38:06.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And Putin is part of that
movement.

38:06.284 --> 38:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the theory of the
